"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A goat which was sent into the wilderness by the high priest, as a symbol of the removal of the sins of the people.</p>\n<h2>The scapegoat as part of an OT ritual</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:7-Lev16:10\">LEV 16:7–16:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:20-Lev16:22\">LEV 16:20–16:22</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:26\">LEV 16:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa53:4\">ISA 53:4</a></p>\n<h2>The scapegoat anticipates Jesus Christ's atonement</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:29\">JHN 1:29</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor5:21\">2CO 5:21</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb9:11-Heb9:14\">HEB 9:11–9:14</a> <em>Jesus Christ's death is here contrasted with the OT sacrificial system.</em></p>",
